    <text>
        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC"><!--update lang and resp here-->              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name nymRef="#maqqas_cairatini"><w>ᚋᚐᚊᚔ</w><w>ᚉᚐᚔᚏᚐᚈᚔᚅᚔ</w></name> 
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:up"/><w type="formula" lemma="avias">ᚐᚃᚔ</w> <name>ᚔᚅᚓᚊᚐᚌᚂᚐᚄ</name></persName>
                </ab> 
            </div>                    
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name  nymRef="#maqqas_cairatini"><w>MAQI</w><w>CAIRATINI</w></name> 
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:up"/><w type="formula" lemma="avias">AVI</w> <name nymRef="#ineqaglasas">INEQAGLAS</name></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app>
<note>According to Macalister (1945, 45) the face of the stone was used for the inscription because there was once an older inscription on the edge of the stone which had continued over the top and concluded on the opposite edge. This older inscription had been intentionally removed, leaving nothing but a few vague traces from which only a bare suggestion that it was in the A maqi mucoi B formula can be recovered. </note>                    
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>'of <persName xml:lang="sga">Mac-Cáirthinn Uí Enechglais</persName>'</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>MAQI- (gen. of MAQ(Q)AS), as a first element meaning 'devotee' or the like, rather than 'son' and <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/7652">cáerthann</ref></foreign> 'rowan tree' (McManus 1991, 108-9). INEQAGLAS, for ENEQ- with addition of a score, (eponym <foreign>Bresal Enechglas</foreign>) 'having a grey face' (McManus 1991, 7, 106). </p>
                <p>The person commemorated here has been identified with a <persName xml:lang="sga">Mac-Cáirthinn</persName> of a Leinster poem who was an <persName xml:lang="sga">Uí Enechglais</persName> king of Leinster and Tara (Carney 1971, 69. n2; Ó Corráin 1985, 62-3; Byrne 1973, 137-8). Although the <persName xml:lang="sga">Uí Enechglais</persName> are located in county Wicklow and this stone comes from Co. Meath, it has been argued that the relegation to the Wicklow coast may have been later (Byrne 1973, 138, 142). This may also be the same <persName xml:lang="sga">Mac-Cárthinn mac Cóelbath</persName> mentioned in the annals in 446, a date which does not fit with the linguistic assessment (McManus 1991, 53, 112). However, a recent possible emendation of the date of the annals puts the entry concerning <persName xml:lang="sga">Mac-Cárthinn mac Cóelbath</persName> to in or around 530, which fits well with the linguistic dating (Eogan and Moore 2008, 304).</p>
                <p>This inscription may be dated to the first half of the sixth century based on the loss of the final -I of INEQAGLAS and its retention in MAQI-CAIRATINI (McManus 1991, 94-5).</p>
            </div>
